<font color="#FF0000">POSSIBILITIES</font><br>
<tt>Tue Oct 28 20:17:51 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Thanks for the clarification, guys..  I have a burnout issue that is dealing with this site.  Most of us that have been here for about a year now go through this cycle.  Passion burns bright, anger and frustration burns white hot, both soon dwindle to a flicker that keeps us aware.  &quot;Lest we forget&quot;. This is usually what it comes down to.  I have worked here (yes, it was at times work) a long time along with other guys like Art and Tom and yes, Barry.<br>
I can't seem to get a handle on the current level of dialog that is going on here. When this thing was new there was a lot of raw emotions that in many cases led to a form of closure and healing. This site seems to have become a sort of e-mail posting facility. I do not want to say that is not good, but as an &quot;old timer&quot; here; to me (my opinion only) this is not what this site was all about.<br>
The way to communicate varies from group to group.  I see a lot of support for each other, but the communications stays on a superficial level.  Once the trust level is built, then discuss the hurt, the pain , the anger, the bitter frustration.  Since this is an open forum, I guess you may use it as you please.  But guys, it seems such a waste. God, there are a 150 threads here.  Where is the SW, Art, Cook , Ed thread that they discuss events that made them who they are today?  Where is the thread that discusses how to recover that lost innocence of youth?  Where is the thread that deals with these guys coming to a resolution to events that occurred 25 to 30 years ago?  It doesn't have to end here but it surely could start here.<br>
Knowing who and what we were enables us to understand what and who we are today.  The stories are vivid. they give us a background but they do no healing.  It is possible that some of us likes what Viet Nam has made us. It is possible that we weathered all the storms of our return with little or no damage. It is possible that to some it is not necessary to heal something that is not broken. <br><br>
                    O.K.<br><br>
 But the original intent of this site was WAS.
